english:
  title: A Memorial Expressing Congratulations on the Auspicious Signs of the Divine Rabbit, Lingzhi Fungus, Propitious Clouds, and Sacred Ice
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Sagely Majesty ascends the throne,
    And harmonious influences flow abundantly forth.
    The cosmic forces nurture the miraculous,
    And auspicious omens arrive in full measure.
    Wherever your radiance reaches,
    All beings dance in perfect accord.

    Looking back through histories of perfect governance,
    It is written that symbols of celestial favor must appear.
    Yet always but a single portent was glimpsed—
    Never before have so many gathered at once.

    Now the sacred rabbit manifests its wonder,
    And the immortal herb displays its brilliance.
    Clouds descend upon the jade palace,
    Wove through with all five colors in swirling mist.
    Ice forms upon the golden river,
    Mirroring the celestial spheres in perfect array.
    These are the signs of your sincere heart touching Heaven,
    The very foundation of eternal peace for all ages.

    Blessings pour upon the ancestral shrine,
    And these events illuminate the pages of history.
    I humbly reflect: Your Majesty possesses
    Proundity and wisdom, strength and purity refined,
    Your governance surpassing all hundred kings of old.
    Rites and music, culture and refinement—all perfected.
    Your grace extends to the eight quarters of the earth,
    And all creatures that fly or dive, move or grow, find peace.

    Thus does the realm receive Heaven's abundant favor,
    And songs of praise overflow from the people's hearts.

    I, your humble servant, though of meager talent,
    Have had the fortune to witness this glorious age.
    My body remains stranded in the eastern seas,
    Unworthy to join the ranks of those who gallop near the throne.
    Yet my heart turns ever northward in reverence,
    And I pour forth the utmost sincerity of my congratulations.
  footnotes:
    - The 'sacred rabbit' (瑞兔), 'lingzhi fungus' (靈芝), 'propitious clouds' (慶雲), and 'sacred ice' (瑞冰) are classical Chinese auspicious omens believed to manifest during the rule of a virtuous sage-king.
    - The 'jade palace' (玉殿) refers to the royal residence; the 'golden river' (金河) likely refers to the Milky Way or a significant celestial or geographical feature.
    - The eight quarters (八表) represent the eight directions or the entire world.
    - '''Flying and diving creatures'' (飛潛) refers to birds and fish, representing all creatures of the earth and water.'
    - The reference to the 'eastern seas' (海東) suggests the author was likely writing from Korea, which in classical Chinese terminology was situated in the east relative to China.
